<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-continuous-functions-on-intervals"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Continuous Functions on Intervals</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The basic properties from the previous section show that continuity is
      preserved under many algebraic operations. When the domain is an
      interval, continuity also has strong global consequences. On a closed
      and bounded interval, a continuous function must stay bounded and must
      attain its largest and smallest values. On any interval, a continuous
      function cannot jump over intermediate values. These results are among
      the first indications that continuity is not merely a local condition.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-extreme-value-theorem">
    <title>Extreme Value Theorem</title>

    <p>
      Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m> and let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m>. We say that
      <m>f</m> attains an <term>absolute maximum</term><idx>absolute
      maximum</idx> on <m>S</m> at <m>c \in S</m> if
      <m>f(x) \le f(c)</m> for every <m>x \in S</m>. Likewise, <m>f</m>
      attains an <term>absolute minimum</term><idx>absolute minimum</idx> on
      <m>S</m> at <m>c</m> if <m>f(c) \le f(x)</m> for every <m>x \in S</m>.
      A function need not attain either one on an arbitrary domain, even if it
      is continuous. Closed and bounded intervals are special because limits of
      sequences in such intervals cannot escape the interval.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-closed-interval-contains-cluster-points">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every cluster point of a closed interval <m>[a,b]</m> belongs to
          <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
	<p> For any <m>c \lt a</m>, let <m>r=(a-c)/2</m>. Then <m>(c-r,c+r)
	  \subseteq (-\infty,a)</m>, which is disjoint from <m>[a,b]</m>. So
	  <m>c</m> is not a cluster point of <m>[a,b]</m>. The case <m>c \gt
	  b</m> is similar, using <m>r=(c-b)/2</m>. Therefore every cluster
	  point of <m>[a,b]</m> must lie in <m>[a,b]</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-continuous-on-closed-bounded-interval-bounded">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every continuous function on a closed bounded interval is bounded.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be continuous. Suppose
          <m>f</m> is not bounded. Then for every <m>n \in \N</m> there
          exists <m>x_n \in [a,b]</m> such that
          <me>|f(x_n)| \gt n.</me>
          Since <m>[a,b]</m> is bounded, <xref ref="thm-bolzano-weierstrass"/>
          gives a convergent subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m>. Let
          <m>x_{n_k} \to c</m>. By
          <xref ref="prop-closed-interval-contains-cluster-points"/>,
          <m>c \in [a,b]</m>. Since <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>,
          <xref ref="prop-sequential-characterization-of-continuity"/> gives
          <m>f(x_{n_k}) \to f(c)</m>. Hence <m>(f(x_{n_k}))</m> is convergent,
          so it is bounded. But
          <m>|f(x_{n_k})| \gt n_k \ge k</m> for every <m>k</m>, which is
          impossible. Therefore <m>f</m> is bounded.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-boundedness-hypotheses-necessary">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Both hypotheses in
          <xref ref="prop-continuous-on-closed-bounded-interval-bounded"/>
          are necessary.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The function <m>f(x)=1/x</m> on <m>(0,1]</m> is continuous, but it
            is not bounded because <m>f(x) \to +\infty</m> as <m>x \to 0^+</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The function
            <me>g(x)=\begin{cases}
              0 &amp; \text{if } x=0,\\
              1/x &amp; \text{if } 0 \lt x \le 1
            \end{cases}</me>
            is defined on the closed bounded interval <m>[0,1]</m>, but it is
            not continuous at <m>0</m> and it is not bounded.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-extreme-value-theorem">
      <title>Extreme Value Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A continuous function on a closed bounded interval attains an
          absolute maximum and an absolute minimum.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
	<p> Let <m>f</m> be continuous on a closed bounded interval
	<m>[a,b]</m>. Then <m>J:=f([a,b])</m> is nonempty and, by <xref
	ref="prop-continuous-on-closed-bounded-interval-bounded"/>, is also
	bounded. So <m>M:=\sup J</m>exists. By <xref
	  ref="prop-sequences-approximate-sup-inf"/>, there is a sequence
	  <m>(y_n)</m> in <m>J</m> that converges to <m>M</m>. For each
	  <m>n</m>, pick <m>x_n \in [a,b]</m> with <m>f(x_n)=y_n</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	  Since <m>[a,b]</m> is bounded, the Bolzano-Weierstrass
	  theorem <xref ref="thm-bolzano-weierstrass"/> yields a
	  convergent subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> of <m>(x_n)</m>. Again
	  <xref ref="prop-closed-interval-contains-cluster-points"/>
	  implies the limit of this subsequence, say <m>c</m>, belongs
	  to <m>[a,b]</m>. Consequently, <m>f</m> is continuous
	  at <m>c</m> and <me>f(x_{n_k}) \to f(c)</me> according
	  to the sequential characterization of continuity <xref
	  ref="prop-sequential-characterization-of-continuity"/>. As a
	  subsequence of <m>(y_n)</m>, <m>f(x_{n_k})=y_{n_k}</m> must converge
	  to <m>M</m> as well. So by uniqueness of limits <m>f(c)=M</m>. Thus,
	  <m>f</m> attains its absolute maximum.
	</p>

        <p>
          Applying the same argument to <m>-f</m>, we see that <m>-f</m>
          attains its absolute maximum at some point <m>d \in [a,b]</m>. Then
          <m>f(d)</m> is the absolute minimum of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-open-interval-no-extrema">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The conclusion of the extreme value theorem can fail if the interval
          is not closed. The identity function <m>f(x)=x</m> on <m>(0,1)</m>
          is continuous and bounded, but it has neither an absolute maximum nor
          an absolute minimum on <m>(0,1)</m>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-open-interval-no-extrema">
          <caption>The graph of <m>f(x)=x</m> on <m>(0,1)</m> has open
          endpoints, so the values <m>0</m> and <m>1</m> are approached but
          never attained.</caption>
          <image width="45%">
            <shortdescription>The line y equals x on the open
            interval from zero to one, with open circles at both
            endpoints.</shortdescription>
	    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=7cm,
  height=6cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-0.1, xmax=1.1,
  ymin=-0.1, ymax=1.1,
  xtick={0,1},
  ytick={0,1},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$},
  domain=0:1,
  samples=2,
  clip=false
]
  \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:1] {x};
  \addplot[only marks, mark=o, mark size=2.5pt, blue] coordinates {(0,0) (1,1)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-intermediate-value-theorem">
    <title>Intermediate Value Theorem</title>

    <p>
      The extreme value theorem says that a continuous function on
      <m>[a,b]</m> cannot avoid its largest and smallest values. The next
      theorem says more: between any two values it takes, it must also take
      every intermediate value. Geometrically, the graph of a continuous
      function on an interval cannot jump across a horizontal line.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-bolzano-zero">
      <title>Bolzano's Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be continuous. If <m>f(a)</m> and
          <m>f(b)</m> are of opposite signs, then there exists
          <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such that <m>f(c)=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          After replacing <m>f</m> by <m>-f</m> if necessary, we may assume
          <m>f(a) \lt 0 \lt f(b)</m>. Let
          <me>S=\{x \in [a,b] : f(x) \lt 0\}.</me>
          Then <m>a \in S</m>, and <m>b</m> is an upper bound of <m>S</m>. So
          <m>c:=\sup S</m> exists. Since <m>a \in S \subseteq [a,b]</m>, we
          have <m>c \in [a,b]</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          We claim that <m>f(c)=0</m>. Suppose first that <m>f(c) \lt 0</m>.
          Then <m>c \lt b</m>, since <m>f(b) \gt 0</m>. Choose a sequence
          <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>(c,b)</m> such that <m>x_n \to c</m>. By
          continuity of <m>f</m> at <m>c</m>, we have
          <m>f(x_n) \to f(c) \lt 0</m>. Hence <m>f(x_n) \lt 0</m> for all
          sufficiently large <m>n</m>. For such <m>n</m>, we have
          <m>x_n \in S</m> and <m>x_n \gt c</m>, contradicting the fact that
          <m>c</m> is an upper bound of <m>S</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now suppose that <m>f(c) \gt 0</m>. Then <m>a \lt c</m>. For each
          <m>n \in \N</m>, let <m>m_n=c-(c-a)/2^n</m>. Then
          <m>m_n \lt c=\sup S</m>, so <m>m_n</m> is not an upper bound of
          <m>S</m>. Therefore there exists <m>x_n \in S</m> such that
          <m>m_n \lt x_n \le c</m>. Since <m>m_n \to c</m> and
          <m>m_n \lt x_n \le c</m> for every <m>n</m>, the squeeze lemma gives
          <m>x_n \to c</m>. By continuity, <m>f(x_n) \to f(c) \gt 0</m>, so
          <m>f(x_n) \gt 0</m> for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>. But each
          <m>x_n \in S</m>, so <m>f(x_n) \lt 0</m> for every <m>n</m>, a
          contradiction.
        </p>

        <p>
          Therefore <m>f(c)=0</m>. Since <m>f(a) \lt 0</m> and
          <m>f(b) \gt 0</m>, we have <m>c \neq a</m> and <m>c \neq b</m>.
          Hence <m>c \in (a,b)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-intermediate-value-theorem">
      <title>Intermediate Value Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be continuous, and let
          <m>\gamma</m> be a real number between <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>.
          Then there exists <m>c \in [a,b]</m> such that
          <me>f(c)=\gamma.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>g(x)=f(x)-\gamma</m>. Then <m>g</m> is
          continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>. If <m>\gamma=f(a)</m> or
          <m>\gamma=f(b)</m>, then we are done. Otherwise <m>\gamma</m> lies
          strictly between <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>, so <m>g(a)</m> and
          <m>g(b)</m> have opposite signs. Hence
          <xref ref="prop-bolzano-zero"/> gives a point <m>c \in (a,b)</m>
          such that <m>g(c)=0</m>. Therefore <m>f(c)=\gamma</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-ivt-equation-root">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The equation <m>x^3+x-1=0</m> has a solution in <m>(0,1)</m>. Indeed,
          the polynomial <m>p(x)=x^3+x-1</m> is continuous, while
          <m>p(0)=-1</m> and <m>p(1)=1</m>. By
          <xref ref="prop-bolzano-zero"/>, there exists <m>c \in (0,1)</m>
          such that <m>p(c)=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-ivt-needs-continuity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Continuity is essential in the intermediate value theorem. Define
          <me>f(x)=\begin{cases}
            -1 &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0,\\
            1 &amp; \text{if } x \ge 0.
          \end{cases}</me>
          Then <m>f(-1)=-1</m> and <m>f(1)=1</m>, but there is no
          <m>c \in [-1,1]</m> with <m>f(c)=0</m>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-jump-discontinuity-no-ivt">
          <caption>A jump discontinuity can skip intermediate values.</caption>
          <image width="48%">
            <shortdescription>The sign function equals negative one to the left of zero and positive one at and to the right of zero, so the graph jumps over zero.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=7cm,
  height=5.6cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-1.4, xmax=1.4,
  ymin=-1.4, ymax=1.4,
  xtick={-1,0,1},
  ytick={-1,0,1},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$},
  clip=false
]
  \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-1.2:0] {-1};
  \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:1.2] {1};
  \addplot[only marks, mark=o, mark size=2.5pt, blue] coordinates {(0,-1)};
  \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, blue] coordinates {(0,1)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-continuous-image-of-interval-is-interval">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The image of an interval under a continuous function is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>I \subseteq \R</m> be an interval, and let
          <m>f \colon I \to \R</m> be continuous. To show that <m>f(I)</m> is
          an interval, let <m>\alpha,\beta \in f(I)</m> with
          <m>\alpha \lt \beta</m>, and let <m>\gamma</m> satisfy
          <m>\alpha \lt \gamma \lt \beta</m>. Choose <m>x_1,x_2 \in I</m>
          such that <m>f(x_1)=\alpha</m> and <m>f(x_2)=\beta</m>. Since
          <m>I</m> is an interval, the closed interval between <m>x_1</m> and
          <m>x_2</m> is contained in <m>I</m>. Applying
          <xref ref="thm-intermediate-value-theorem"/> to the restriction of
          <m>f</m> to that closed interval, we obtain
          <m>c \in I</m> such that <m>f(c)=\gamma</m>. Thus
          <m>\gamma \in f(I)</m>, so <m>f(I)</m> is an interval.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-continuous-image-of-closed-bounded-interval">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The image of a closed bounded interval under a continuous function is
          a closed bounded interval.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be continuous. By
          <xref ref="cor-continuous-image-of-interval-is-interval"/>,
          <m>f([a,b])</m> is an interval. By
          <xref ref="thm-extreme-value-theorem"/>, <m>f</m> attains its
          absolute minimum <m>m</m> and absolute maximum <m>M</m> on
          <m>[a,b]</m>. Hence <m>f([a,b]) \subseteq [m,M]</m>. Since
          <m>f([a,b])</m> is an interval containing <m>m</m> and <m>M</m>, it
          also contains every number between them. Therefore
          <m>[m,M] \subseteq f([a,b])</m>, and so
          <me>f([a,b])=[m,M].</me>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <p>
      The last corollary is a first glimpse of a more general theorem from
      topology: continuous images of compact sets are compact. For subsets of
      <m>\R</m>, compactness is the same as being closed and bounded, so the
      corollary above is exactly the one-dimensional case of that general
      principle.
    </p>

    <proposition
    xml:id="prop-injective-continuous-on-interval-has-continuous-inverse">
    <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is injective and continuous on an interval <m>I</m>,
          then the inverse of <m>f \colon I \to f(I)</m> is also continuous.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
	<p>
	  Clearly, we can assume <m>I</m> is non-degenerated (i.e. has at
	  least two points). Let <m>g \colon f(I) \to I</m> be the inverse
	  of <m>f</m>.	We argue that <m>g</m> is continuous at an arbitrary
	  point <m>y_0 \in f(I)</m>. Let <m>(y_n)</m> be a sequence in
	  <m>f(I)</m> that converges to <m>y_0</m>. Set <m>x_n=g(y_n)</m>
	  and <m>x_0=g(y_0)</m>. We must show that <m>x_n \to x_0</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	  Suppose, to the contrary, that <m>x_n</m> does not converge to
	  <m>x_0</m>. Then there exists <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> such that
	  infinitely many terms of the sequence <m>(x_n)</m> lie outside the
	  interval <m>I_0 := (x_0-\varepsilon, x_0+\varepsilon) \cap I</m>.
	  Passing to a subsequence, we may assume that
	  <m>x_{n_k} \notin I_0</m> for every <m>k</m>. Since <m>x_0</m> is a
	  point of a non-degenerated interval, it is a cluster point of
	  <m>I</m>, and hence <m>I_0</m> is also non-degenerated. By <xref
	  ref="cor-continuous-image-of-interval-is-interval"/>, <m>f(I_0)</m>
	  is an interval containing <m>y_0</m>; it is also non-degenerated
	  because <m>f</m> is injective. Therefore there exists
	  <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
	  <me>(y_0-\delta,y_0+\delta)\cap f(I) \subseteq f(I_0).</me>
	  But <m>y_{n_k}=f(x_{n_k})</m> and <m>x_{n_k} \notin I_0</m>, so
	  <m>y_{n_k} \notin f(I_0)</m> for every <m>k</m>. On the other hand,
	  since <m>y_{n_k} \to y_0</m> and each <m>y_{n_k}</m> lies in
	  <m>f(I)</m>, we have <m>y_{n_k} \in f(I_0)</m> for all sufficiently
	  large <m>k</m>, a contradiction.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>
</section>
